Ach-laut, a phoneme found in both German and Hebrew that is produced with high subglottal pressure in which the back of the tongue interacts with the soft palate (it has no equivalent in English). It is employed after the written vowels a, o, u or the diphthong au. Examples include the German words Nacht and hoch.